{
  "answer": "**The poem \"Vainglory\" (chapter 12 of *Old English Elegies*) opens by describing a prophetic teaching on how to distinguish two kinds of men: \"God's own child, a welcome guest,\" from \"the weaker one also, burdened by sin.\"**[^1]\n\nThis contrast plays out in a classic Anglo-Saxon mead-hall scene (\"wine-halls,\" \"symbel,\" \"hall,\" \"feast\"), where warriors gather, drink, boast, and reveal their inner natures: \"Clamor rises, shouting in the troop... So are their spirits variously divided; the retainers are unalike.\" The vainglorious man (\"fiend's own child\") swells with pride, envy, and malice at the feast,[^2] while the humble man (\"God's own child\") lives in peace and earns heavenly reward.[^3]\n\nThe entire instructional passage functions as a moral \"riddle\" for identifying these types amid the revelry—no separate riddle poem exists within it.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Vainglory,\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/12-vainglory/translation/#p-946b37).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Vainglory,\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/12-vainglory/translation/#p-946b37).\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Vainglory,\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/12-vainglory/translation/#p-946b37).",
